## READ FIRST: `SURFACE_CONTRACT.md`

Surface is a **slime**: shape-free (UI / API / MCP / bot / dashboard / wizard / anything), invariants-bound. The canonical contract is `SURFACE_CONTRACT.md` in the repo root.

## ABSOLUTE rule #0 — Yggdrasil scope vs Backend scope

Yggdrasil (and surfaces) = IDP for the operating company's internal team. Backend = end-user-facing business. A surface views/dispatches operations on COMPANY-OWNED resources for the INTERNAL team. It is never an end-user product frontend.

Example: "Stripe webhook health dashboard for platform team" → Yggdrasil surface. "Pay your bill page for customers" → operator product frontend (NOT Yggdrasil). Heuristic: if audience is the COMPANY's internal team → Yggdrasil surface; if audience is END-USERS → not Yggdrasil.

## Invariants

- **Stateless w.r.t. business** — business state strongly discouraged; if absolutely needed, ADR + sign-off (§5.1).
- **Auth via Yggdrasil session** — delegated; public surfaces use read-only Yggdrasil tokens.
- **Backend-agnostic** — calls Yggdrasil core `/api/v1/*`. Direct provider API calls strongly discouraged; ADR + sign-off (§5.2) if absolutely needed.
- **Multi-tenant aware** — `integration_instance` scoping respected.
- **Lego principle** — no hardcoded cloud / CDN / auth / analytics / i18n provider.
- **No business decisions** — surface presents and dispatches; doesn't decide business rules.

## Hard line (no exceptions)

- NEVER log credentials, secrets, signing keys, tokens.
- NEVER reimplement user auth from scratch.
- NEVER hardcode a specific cloud / CDN / hosting / auth provider.
- NEVER make business decisions.

## Freedoms (slime adapts)

- Any framework (React, Vue, Svelte, server-rendered, anything)
- Any shape (UI, API-only, MCP, bot, hybrid)
- Any real-time mechanism (SSE, WebSocket, polling)
- UX-edge persistence (localStorage, IndexedDB) for non-business state
- Custom data shaping, aggregations, cross-integration views
- New surface "shapes" don't need permission — invariants do

## Working in this scaffold

- Keep defaults generic, portable, production-friendly.
- Preserve readiness, timeouts, graceful shutdown.
- Don't bake product-specific business logic into the template.
